  "prompt": "I am a third year mu engineering student. I have one kt in semester 2 will I get grace?",
  "response": "In many engineering colleges in India, especially those affiliated with universities like Mumbai University (MU), the concept of \"grace marks\" is applied to help students clear a subject if they are short by a small margin. However, whether you will get grace marks depends on specific rules and policies of your university and college.\n\nHere\u2019s what you should consider:\n\n1. **University/College Rules**: Check your university\u2019s or college\u2019s examination rules regarding grace marks. Some institutions offer a few (e.g., 5\u201310) grace marks to help students clear a subject if they are just short of the passing marks.\n\n2. **KT Subject**: If you have a KT (Keep Term, meaning you failed) in Semester 2, you may be eligible for grace marks if you are short by a small margin (e.g., 1\u20135 marks). However, this varies by institution.\n\n3. **Academic Performance**: Some colleges grant grace marks based on overall academic performance in other subjects or semesters.\n\n4. **Backlog Policy**: If grace marks are not applicable, you may need to clear the KT by reappearing for the exam in the next available attempt.\n\n5. **Consult Your Department**: Reach out to your academic advisor, faculty, or examination department for clarification on grace marks and backlog policies.\n\nIn summary, you might get grace marks depending on your university\u2019s rules and how close you were to passing. However, it\u2019s essential to confirm with your college or university authorities. If grace marks are not applicable, you\u2019ll need to clear the KT by reappearing for the exam.",
